              <tr><td><strong>CRO</strong></td><td>Converting existing traffic</td><td>Conversion rate, revenue per visitor</td><td>Growth / product team</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>SXO</strong></td><td>The full journey from query to conversion</td><td>Organic revenue, qualified organic leads</td><td>Cross-functional</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>UX</strong></td><td>Usability and satisfaction</td><td>Task completion, CSAT, NPS</td><td>Product / design team</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real SXO examples</h2>

        <h3>Dental practice — tripled calls from same ranking</h3>
        <p>A dental practice ranking #1 for "dentist near downtown Austin" received few calls. An audit revealed slow mobile load times (6.2 seconds), phone numbers buried below the fold, and no above-the-fold CTAs. After SXO optimization — compressing images, adding a sticky call button, and restructuring the hero section to lead with "Book today, same-day appointments available" — call volume tripled from the same ranking position with no additional SEO work.</p>

        <h3>B2B SaaS — 3x demo requests with same content volume</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS company publishing 30 articles monthly added internal product links, embedded demo CTAs within relevant content sections, and created clear next-step guidance at the end of each article. Result: 3x more demo requests compared to competitors publishing similar content volume without an SXO conversion layer.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">SXO vs traditional SEO — the difference in practice</h2>
        <p>Both aim to generate business from search. The practical difference is the scope of optimization and the metrics used to judge success.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Traditional SEO focus</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Keyword targeting and ranking position</li>
              <li>Backlink building and domain authority</li>
              <li>Technical crawlability and indexability</li>
              <li>Organic traffic volume</li>
              <li>Success = higher rankings, more impressions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>SXO extends to</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Page load speed and Core Web Vitals</li>
              <li>Intent matching and content relevance</li>
              <li>CTA placement and conversion path</li>
              <li>Engagement metrics: time-on-page, scroll depth, bounce rate</li>
              <li>Success = organic leads, revenue, and qualified conversions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for SXO implementation</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Audit intent alignment before optimizing experience.</strong> A perfectly fast page targeting the wrong intent still bounces. Verify SERP intent first, then optimize the experience layer.</li>
          <li><strong>Fix Core Web Vitals to passing status (LCP under 2.5s, INP under 200ms, CLS under 0.1).</strong> These are the Google-defined thresholds. Below them, you have a ranking disadvantage regardless of content quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Place the primary CTA above the fold on mobile.</strong> Over 60% of organic traffic arrives on mobile. If the phone number, contact form, or demo link requires scrolling, conversion rates drop measurably.</li>
          <li><strong>Write page titles and meta descriptions that match the page content exactly.</strong> The click-to-bounce pipeline starts when a title promises something the page does not deliver. Accurate titles reduce bounce rates and improve engagement metrics.</li>
          <li><strong>Use internal linking to guide users to the next logical step.</strong> A blog post reader who has finished your article should have an obvious next page that deepens their engagement — a related guide, a product comparison, or a case study.</li>
          <li><strong>Measure organic conversion rate separately from overall conversion rate.</strong> Organic visitors often have different intent than paid visitors. Track them separately to see the true SXO impact.</li>
          <li><strong>Run page-level audits on your highest-traffic, lowest-converting organic pages.</strong> These pages already have SEO traction — SXO optimization on them has the fastest payback of any content investment.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — optimizing for rankings, ignoring what happens after the click</div>
          <p>Many SEO campaigns celebrate traffic milestones without measuring what that traffic does. A page receiving 10,000 visits per month with a 0.2% conversion rate underperforms a page with 2,000 visits at 3%. Always connect organic traffic to business outcomes — otherwise you cannot prioritize where SXO work will have the greatest impact.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common SXO mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Treating SEO and UX as separate disciplines</strong> — they share ranking signals; optimizing one without the other leaves value on the table</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring mobile experience</strong> — Google indexes mobile-first; a desktop-optimized page with poor mobile UX has a structural ranking disadvantage</li>
          <li><strong>Generic CTAs ("Learn more", "Click here")</strong> — specific, benefit-driven CTAs ("See how fast your site loads") convert significantly better</li>
          <li><strong>No above-the-fold CTA on service pages</strong> — intent-matched visitors are ready to convert immediately; making them scroll to find the contact option loses them</li>
          <li><strong>Slow page speed on high-traffic pages</strong> — every additional second of load time costs 4.42% in conversion rate</li>
          <li><strong>Not tracking engagement metrics in GSC and Analytics together</strong> — ranking data alone does not tell you if traffic is productive</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
